Lections were, in the first instance, taken from the books of the Bible itseff, either as isolated texts or grouped in divers manners. The president of the congregation chose the passages to be read, and he stopped the reader when he thought proper. Later on there was an assigned text, of which the length had been previously determined, for every Sunday and festival. This did not prevent, however, the employment of books with complete texts, in which it was enough to indicate either on the margin, or in a table placed at the commencement, the beginning and end of the lessons belonging to the Sunday or holy day. This table was designated in Greek by the term Synaaeargsff and in Latin by that of Capitulary.
